<doc id="27593" wikidata="Q625303" url="?curid=27593" title="Independence (probability theory)">
<text>Independence is a fundamental notion in probability theory, as in statistics and the theory of stochastic processes. Two events are independent, statistically independent, or stochastically independent if, informally speaking, the occurrence of one does not affect the probability of occurrence of the other or, equivalently, does not affect the odds. Similarly, two random variables are independent if the realization of one does not affect the probability distribution of the other.

When dealing with collections of more than two events, two notions of independence need to be distinguished. The events are called pairwise independent if any two events in the collection are independent of each other, while mutual independence (or collective independence) of events means, informally speaking, that each event is independent of any combination of other events in the collection. A similar notion exists for collections of random variables. Mutual independence implies pairwise independence, but not the other way around. In the standard literature of probability theory, statistics, and stochastic processes, independence without further qualification usually refers to mutual independence.

==Definition==
===For events===
====Two events====
Two events formula_1 and formula_2 are independent (often written as formula_3 or formula_4, where the latter symbol often is also used for conditional independence) if and only if their joint probability equals the product of their probabilities:

formula_5 indicates that two independent events formula_1 and formula_2 have common elements in their sample space so that they are not mutually exclusive (mutually exclusive iff formula_8). Why this defines independence is made clear by rewriting with conditional probabilities formula_9 as the probability at which the event formula_1 occurs provided that the event formula_2 has or is assumed to have occurred:

:formula_12

and similarly

:formula_13

Thus, the occurrence of formula_2 does not affect the probability of formula_1, and vice versa. In other words, formula_1 and formula_2 are independent of each other. Although the derived expressions may seem more intuitive, they are not the preferred definition, as the conditional probabilities may be undefined if formula_18 or formula_19 are 0. Furthermore, the preferred definition makes clear by symmetry that when formula_1 is independent of formula_2, formula_2 is also independent of formula_1.

====Odds====
Stated in terms of odds, two events are independent if and only if the odds ratio of and is unity (1). Analogously with probability, this is equivalent to the conditional odds being equal to the unconditional odds:
:formula_24
or to the odds of one event, given the other event, being the same as the odds of the event, given the other event not occurring:
:formula_25
The odds ratio can be defined as
:formula_26
or symmetrically for odds of given , and thus is 1 if and only if the events are independent.

====More than two events====
A finite set of events formula_27 is pairwise independent if every pair of events is independent—that is, if and only if for all distinct pairs of indices formula_28,

A finite set of events is mutually independent if every event is independent of any intersection of the other events—that is, if and only if for every formula_29 and for every k indices formula_30,

This is called the &quot;multiplication rule&quot; for independent events. It is not a single condition involving only the product of all the probabilities of all single events; it must hold true for all subsets of events.

For more than two events, a mutually independent set of events is (by definition) pairwise independent; but the converse is not necessarily true.

====Log probability and information content====
Stated in terms of log probability, two events are independent if and only if the log probability of the joint event is the sum of the log probability of the individual events:
:formula_31
In information theory, negative log probability is interpreted as information content, and thus two events are independent if and only if the information content of the combined event equals the sum of information content of the individual events:
:formula_32
See &quot;&quot; for details.

===For real valued random variables===
====Two random variables====
Two random variables formula_33 and formula_34 are independent if and only if (iff) the elements of the -system generated by them are independent; that is to say, for every formula_35 and formula_36, the events formula_37 and formula_38 are independent events (as defined above in ). That is, formula_33 and formula_34 with cumulative distribution functions formula_41 and formula_42, are independent iff the combined random variable formula_43 has a joint cumulative distribution function

or equivalently, if the probability densities formula_44 and formula_45 and the joint probability density formula_46 exist,

:formula_47

====More than two random variables====
A finite set of formula_48 random variables formula_49 is pairwise independent if and only if every pair of random variables is independent. Even if the set of random variables is pairwise independent, it is not necessarily &quot;mutually independent&quot; as defined next.

A finite set of formula_48 random variables formula_49 is mutually independent if and only if for any sequence of numbers formula_52, the events formula_53 are mutually independent events (as defined above in ). This is equivalent to the following condition on the joint cumulative distribution function A finite set of formula_48 random variables formula_49 is mutually independent if and only if

It is not necessary here to require that the probability distribution factorizes for all possible subsets as in the case for formula_48 events. This is not required because e.g. formula_57 implies formula_58.

The measure-theoretically inclined reader may prefer to substitute events formula_59 for events formula_60 in the above definition, where formula_1 is any Borel set. That definition is exactly equivalent to the one above when the values of the random variables are real numbers. It has the advantage of working also for complex-valued random variables or for random variables taking values in any measurable space (which includes topological spaces endowed by appropriate σ-algebras).

