where (x_1,\ldots,x_n) = \mathrm{P}(X(t_1) \leq x_1,\ldots,X(t_n) \leq x_n)&lt;/math&gt;.}} Independence of a stochastic process is a property &quot;within&quot; a stochastic process, not between two stochastic processes.

====For two stochastic processes====
Independence of two stochastic processes is a property between two stochastic processes formula_78 and formula_82 that are defined on the same probability space formula_83. Formally, two stochastic processes formula_78 and formula_82 are said to be independent if for all formula_79 and for all formula_80, the random vectors formula_88 and formula_89 are independent, i.e. if

(x_1,\ldots,x_n) \cdot F_{Y_{t_1},\ldots,Y_{t_n}}(y_1,\ldots,y_n) \quad \text{for all } x_1,\ldots,x_n&lt;/math&gt;|}}
